data.survey.strategy: Looking for a lead ...
Try to see evidence objectively
It was really fun, but at moments I was overwhelmed with information.
random
I tried to look for consistencies between my clues and the clues of the other players
Use a balance of evidence to see who was more likely to commit the crime.
I used process of elimination and put what I thought to be useless clues in the dead ends section and used the majority of the person I thought did it and pieced it all together up in possible leads
I was trying to build a chain of events and motives. I feel I didn't get much description about body type at all.

Once I had a "hunch" as to the clues I felt were most important, I really narrowed my focus.  As I think back, that may not have been the best strategy as I could have missed some valuable clues that didn't fit my narrative.
I tried to connect each phrase or idea with similar ones
Look for common clues from the collaborators
It was not well planned,
I looked at the clues.
I thought about what made sense and evidence was observed.
read and deduce
I tried to keep the pieces together and clues that agreed with other clues were placed in the relevant section
look for clues that repeated
trying to see if the clues fit in my opinion
Find stuff that fits
I based most of my decisions on the one clue that said "Evidence shows the case was opened with a tire iron."
I was trying to see which clues made more sense.
I just used my best judgment
Determine getaway vehicle first
tried to find clues that tied together
I constantly reviewed the information of all three collaborators, and selectively chose the best options among them as I proceeded.
I tried to piece the clues together.
Try my best to piece together motives and tie them to descriptions of people seen at the casino.
Noted every ones view and having vivid imagination over the scenarios.
I tried to look for pure facts a opposed to irrelevant info. Attempted to determine as many false leads as possible to determine the actual facts I could work with
If it had something to do with the FBI I figured it was a good lead. If there was just a sighting or something with not much value I figured it was not important.
i looked for clues that were related to what was found at the crime scene
